Q2. Document the incident, response actions, and mitigation strategies. [15M]
Incident Report
Incident: Rogue Access Point Found in Lobby
Date: October 28, 2024
Reported By: Network Security Team

What Happened
An unauthorized wireless router was found plugged into a network jack in the company lobby. It was active for 2 hours before detection. Two employee laptops connected to it during that time, potentially exposing internal network traffic.

How We Responded
Time	Action
10:00 AM	Alert received: rogue AP detected.
10:05 AM	Confirmed device is unauthorized.
10:08 AM	Disabled the network port remotely.
10:15 AM	Security found and removed the device.
10:30 AM	Blocked device MAC address.
11:00 AM	Scanned affected employee laptops.
Root Cause
Unsecured network jack in a public area.

No authentication required on wired ports (anyone could plug in).

VLAN misconfiguration — the lobby port had access to internal systems instead of being isolated.

Mitigation Strategies
Immediate Fixes (Done)
Disabled all unused network jacks in public areas.

Changed VLAN on lobby ports to guest network only (no internal access).

Long-Term Fixes (To Implement)
Strategy	How It Helps
802.1X / NAC	Requires devices to authenticate before gaining network access. Blocks rogue devices automatically.
Monthly sweeps	Security team physically checks public areas for hidden devices.
Wireless intrusion prevention	Automatically detects and blocks rogue APs without manual intervention.
Employee awareness	Train staff to report unknown network devices.
Conclusion
The breach was contained quickly with no data loss or malware infection. The incident highlighted the need for better physical port security and network access controls. All recommended fixes are scheduled for implementation.

